            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1948-11-22T12:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1948-11-22T12:00:00-05:00" n="754" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d754">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">125.6336/11–1848: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Consul General at Mukden</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ward</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1948-11-22T12:00:00-05:00">November 22, 1948—noon</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>216. Dept judges your unnumbered tel 4 p. m. 18th<note n="56" xml:id="d754fn56">See telegram No. 2464, November 18, from the Consul General at Shanghai,
                            <ref target="#pg_837">p. 837</ref>.</note> Communists have seized and
                    taken physical possession your radio transmitter and notes essential difference
                    between ordering you cease use radio and outright seizure US Govt property. Dept
                    takes serious view latter action and suggests unless you consider such action
                    unwise you protest vigorously this or any other seizure US Govt property,
                    keeping in mind Deptel 187 Nov 2.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lovett</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
